liberal education during the panel, “My Parents Say I Can’t Study That: Helping Students Find Their Intellectual Home in an Era of Parental Skepticism.”\n','full_html'),('node','article',0,266,266,'und',0,'<Description><p>The 2012 book “<a href=\"http://bit.ly/2dDOyXd\">The Refusal of Politics</a>” by <a href=\"http://romancestudies.cornell.edu/people/faculty-directory/laurent-dubreuil/\">Laurent Dubreuil</a>, professor of Romance studies and comparative literature, has been translated into English by Cory Browning PhD \'15 and released by Edinburgh University Press. In the work, Dubreuil develops a conceptual critique of today\'s democracy and social order, calling for a qualified refusal of politics that would make our lives more livable. He particularly explores the connection between literature, the arts and the political while reconsidering the limits of politics.</p>\n<p>Dubreuil’s research examines how literature is an expression of thought that defies the boundaries of rationality and responds to the disciplines of knowledge. Dubreuil has reading ability in more than seven languages. He frequently works on French &amp; Francophone literature, classical Greek texts, Continental theory, philosophy and social thought. He is also invested in furthering a theoretical dialogue between cognitive science and the humanities. He is the author of six books of philosophy and literary theory, including “The Intellective Space” (2015) and “Empire of Language” (2013). Having served as the editor-at-large of Labyrinthe, an interdisciplinary journal, he is currently the editor of diacritics. A \"reader\" and collection of essays on Dubreuil\'s work has recently been published in France under the title \"L\'empire de la littérature\" (2016).</p>\n</Description>','The 2012 book “The Refusal of Politics” by Laurent Dubreuil, professor of Romance studies and comparative literature, has bee','full_html'),('node','article',0,266,326,'und',0,'<Description><p>The 2012 book “<a href=